# Minimal and Safe Editing

Apply this every time you edit code, reply, commit, or open a PR. It covers
scope, style, interfaces, contracts, encoding, and text fidelity.

## Core principle

Make only the changes the user explicitly requested in the current message;
keep style stable and leave everything else byte-for-byte unchanged.

## Procedure for every edit

1. List the exact files and changes the request names.
2. If a change is not on that list, do not make it; ask first.
3. Make the smallest diff that satisfies the request; touch only those regions.
4. If your change breaks compile, test, or runtime, fix only that breakage, in
   the smallest scope.
5. Before sending, run the checks in "Validate before sending".

- If the request is a question or review only, do not edit any file.
- If the request is ambiguous or scope is unclear, stop and ask.
- Debugging does not expand scope.

## Do not, unless explicitly requested

- Refactor, rename, or move code.
- Extract constants, helpers, or functions.
- Reformat, reflow, reorder imports, or edit whitespace.
- Edit comments that are not part of the requested change.
- Change defaults, entry points, or control flow.
- Replace a working approach with a different one.
- Delete files, or add or remove dependencies or versions.
- Change CI, env vars, or settings.
- Add tests, docs, or new files.

## Interfaces and contracts

Treat anything other code, scripts, or users depend on as a fixed contract:
filenames, log names, package-list paths, redirect targets, exported names and
function signatures, CLI flags and argument order, env var names, config and
JSON/YAML keys, command strings, exit codes, and parseable log or output text.

- Do not rename, reorder, or restructure a contract while making an unrelated
  change.
- Preserve existing command invocations verbatim. Example: do not swap a bulk
  command for a loop, or change flags, unless the user asks.
- To change a contract, stop and ask first, then update every caller and
  consumer in the same change. These are not harmless refactors.

## Encoding and text fidelity

Applies to all text you write or edit: code, comments, docs, chat, commits, PRs.

- Preserve original file encoding and line endings.
- Never rewrite or re-encode untouched text, including non-ASCII text (e.g. GBK,
  UTF-8 comments, copyright or bullet symbols).
- On new or modified lines, use ASCII punctuation only. Do not introduce smart
  quotes, em or en dash, ellipsis char, full-width punctuation, Unicode bullets,
  or non-ASCII arrows.
- Do not change or normalize punctuation in existing text unless asked.
- Do not make style-only punctuation edits in comments, docs, or strings.
- If you detect encoding corruption, restore the original characters from the
  base content; do not "fix" it by normalizing punctuation.
- Do not reflow or wrap untouched lines. Wrap only a line you functionally edit,
  and only when it aids correctness or local readability, or when asked.
- All plan documents must use UTF-8 encoding by default (no BOM preferred),
  including new `*plan*.md` files.

## Planning and execution

- If the user asks for a direct fix, implement it. Do not substitute a long plan
  or multi-option review unless they asked for planning.
- Do not switch to Plan mode or broaden the task with extra refactors,
  follow-ups, or optional improvements unless asked or scope is unclear.
- Do not start long builds, installs, or full test suites unless asked, or to
  run a minimal check that verifies your requested change.

## Commits and pull requests (only when asked)

- Stage only files that belong to the requested change; do not bundle unrelated
  work.
- Commit title: read recent `git log` and match this repo's title style only
  (short summary; accurate verbs: add, fix, update, remove).
- Commit body: always include a detailed `- ` bullet list of what changed.
  Wrap body lines at 80 columns.
- When amending, keep the title format; update the title only if the change
  scope warrants it. Always rewrite the body as a fresh detailed `- ` bullet
  list of what is in the commit, wrapped at 80 columns.
- PR title: short summary. PR body: `- ` bullets for Summary and Test plan;
  complete sentences; ASCII punctuation only.

## Formatting for new prose

- Line width: follow `.editorconfig`, then workspace or Cursor settings; else
  aim for commit/PR text and comments around 80 characters. This is a soft
  guide, not a hard limit; overflow when wrapping would hurt readability.
- Use `- ` bullets in commit/PR bodies.

## Validate before sending

Before sending a reply or creating a commit or PR:

- Re-scan the diff and drafted text for mojibake, replacement characters, and
  non-ASCII punctuation on new or modified lines.
- Confirm every changed region maps to something the user requested.
- If anything fails, fix or restore it before sending.
